 BY BAMIDELE FAMOOFO Nigeria’s Gross Domestic Product numbers for fourth quarter in 2021recorded a growth of 3.98% year-on-year, marking the fifth consecutive quarter of growth after the COVID-19 induced recession in third quarter in 2020. Real GDP in third quarter of 2021 printed 4.03% while the figure was 0.11% in fourth quarter of 2020.  Meanwhile, GDP for full year 2021 stood at 3.40% compare with 1.92% in the same period in 2020. Analysing the breakdown provided, financial experts at Cordros Research noted that the oil sector’s woes remain intact as it contracted 8.06% y/ compare with -19.76% in Q4-20. According to the NBS, crude oil production averaged 1.50mb/d in Q4-21, 3.8% y/y lower than Q4-20 (1.56mb/d). The oil sector contributed 5.19% to total GDP (vs Q4-20: 5.87%) during the review period. Elsewhere, the non-oil sector grew by 4.73% y/y in Q4-21 (vs 1.69% in Q4-20). The non-oil sector contributed 94.81% to total GDP (vs 94.13% and 92.51% in Q4-20 and Q3-21, respectively). Analysing the breakdown of three of the most significant components of the GDP: Agriculture grew stronger by 3.58% y/y (vs +1.22% y/y in Q3-21); Industries contracted by 0.05% y/y, (vs -1.63% y/y in Q3-21); while Services grew by 5.58% (vs +8.41% y/y in Q3-21). In terms of contribution, services, agriculture, and industries, respectively, accounted for 55.11%, 26.84%, and 18.05% of overall output. 